Hmm, we're kinda stumped by C and its diversity of structures for representing time, and then the disjoint sets of functionality associated with each.

I'm wondering if we're better of with something like the following so we don't get caught out by overflow or mixed types:

```
static void timespec_to_timeval(const struct timespec *ts, struct timeval *tv)
{
    tv.tv_sec = ts->tv_sec;
    tv.tv_usec = ts->tv_nsec / 1000;
}

static int clock_gettimeval(clockid_t clockid, struct timeval *tv)
{
    struct timespec now;
    int rc;

    rc = clock_gettime(clockid, &now);
    if (rc < 0) {
        return rc;
    }

    timespec_to_timeval(&now, tv);

    return 0;
}
```

From here we can do everything in terms of the `struct timeval`s and [take advantage of its helper functions][1]:

[1]: https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/timeradd.3.html

```
    static const struct timeval max_response_interval = {
        .tv_sec = 4,
        .tv_usec = 6000000
    };
    struct timeval nowval, endval;

    ...

    rc = clock_gettimeval(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, &nowval);
    if (rc < 0) {
         return -errno;
    }

    rc = timeradd(&nowval, &max_response_timeout, &endval);
    if (rc < 0) {
        return -errno;
    }

    do {
        ...

        rc = clock_gettimeval(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, &nowval);
        if (rc < 0) {
            return -errno;
        }
    } while (!timercmp(&nowval, &endval, <));

    if (!timercmp(&nowval, &endval, >=)) {
        return -ETIMEDOUT;
    }

    ...
```

It's more code, but it gets us idiomatic use of existing library functions. Again that helps mitigate overflow and mixed types.

